05091nam a22008055i 9780823275878DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20172017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232758787 a10.1515/97808232758782doi  a(DE-B1597)555256  a(OCoLC)976434310  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBT50b.M275513 2017eb 7aREL0670002bisacsh04a231/.0422231 aMarion, Jean-Luc, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBelieving in Order to See :bOn the Rationality of Revelation and the Irrationality of Some Believers /cJean-Luc Marion. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives in Continental Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tTranslator's Note -- tPART I. Reason and Faith Together -- t1 Faith and Reason -- t2 In Defense of Argument -- t3 The Formal Reason of the Infinite -- tPART II. Who Speaks about It? -- t4 On the Eminent Dignity of the Poor Baptized -- t5 The Service of Rationality in the Church -- t6 The Future of Catholicism -- tPART III. What Is Possible and What Shows Itself -- t7 Nothing Is Impossible for God -- t8 The Phenomenality of the Sacrament -- t9 Transcendence par Excellence -- tPART IV. Recognition -- t10 The Recognition of the Gift -- t11 "They Recognized Him and He Became Invisible to Them" -- t12 The Invisible Saint -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFaith and reason, especially in Roman Catholic thought, are less contradictory today than ever. But does the supposed opposition even make sense to begin with? One can lose faith, but surely not because one gains in reason. Some, in fact, lose faith when reason is not able to make sense of the experiences of our lives. We very quickly realize that reason does not understand everything. Immense areas remain incomprehensible and irrational, which we abandon to belief and opinion.Soon we definitively renounce thinking what that has been excluded from the realm of the thinkable. Ideological nightmares arise from this slumber of reason. Thus, the separation between faith and reason, too quickly taken as self-evident and even natural, is born from a lack of rationality, an easy capitulatin of reason before what is supposedly unthinkable. Rather than lose faith through excessive rationality, we often lose rationality because faith is too quickly excluded from the realm that it claims to open, that of revelation. We lose reason by losing faith.Examining such topics as the role of the intellectual in the church, the rationality of faith, the infinite worth and incomprehensibility of the human, the phenomenality of the sacraments, and the phenomenological nature of miracles and of revelation more broadly, this book spans the range of Marion's thought on Christianity. Throughout he stresses that faith has its own rationality, structured according to the logic of the gift that calls forth a response of love and devotion through kenotic abandon.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aFaith and reasonxChristianity. 0aPhilosophy and religion. 0aRevelationxChristianity. 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / General.2bisacsh  aCatholicism.  aEucharist.  afaith.  agift.  agivenness.  aphenomenality.  aphenomenon.  arevelation.  asacrament.1 aGschwandtner, Christina M.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311072901640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823275878zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823275878423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823275878.jpg  a978